At first you need to get the number of exporters and then loop over them:

```
Assimp::Exporter exporter;
auto numExporters = GetExportFormatCount();
int objIdx = -1;
for ( auto i=0; i< numExporters; i++ ) {
  const aiExportFormatDesc* format = exporter.GetExportFormatDescription(i);
  if ( 0 == strncmp("obj ), format->id, 3 ) {
    objIdx = i;
    break;
  }
}
```
Then you will get the needed information.

You will find the information at Exporter.hpp:

```
    /** Returns a description of the nth export file format. Use #
     *  #Exporter::GetExportFormatCount to learn how many export
     *  formats are supported.
     *
     * The returned pointer is of static storage duration if the
     * pIndex pertains to a built-in exporter (i.e. one not registered
     * via #RegistrerExporter). It is restricted to the life-time of the
     * #Exporter instance otherwise.
     *
     * @param pIndex Index of the export format to retrieve information
     *  for. Valid range is 0 to #Exporter::GetExportFormatCount
     * @return A description of that specific export format.
     *  NULL if pIndex is out of range. */

```

@loechel the idea is that we have the docs always in the repository of the package it does not matter if it's core or collective, further setup is, that we fetch the docs from the repo and include it into docs.plone.org, like we do it already for certrain packages, the difference between core and collective is, that we include docs from core packages and link to collective packages, this approach is 'newish'.

The whole idea is, that is would be easier to keep the docs up2date, because we wo not have to change them on different locations.

So for now we do not have to setup something, if I get a 'good to go' I will link them from both locations, for now, if solr is moving to core, I will change the link to a include the docs and make a reference.

